26
00:02:34,020 --> 00:02:39,380
of five different people in the congregations. It's an African-American congregation, and

27
00:02:39,380 --> 00:02:44,160
they have local ordinations very often in their churches, and that's what this was.

28
00:02:44,160 --> 00:02:51,680
But the two churches came together to ordain these five within their congregations.

29
00:02:52,540 --> 00:02:55,740
And the entire thing was done with unity.

30
00:02:56,340 --> 00:02:58,720
It was a marvelous thing to see what God had done.

31
00:02:59,180 --> 00:03:03,020
And now the daughter church speaks of being the daughter of the mother church.

32
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:06,420
And that sometimes the labor process is painful.

33
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,740
But God brought forth a new church through it.

34
00:03:10,140 --> 00:03:13,060
And now they're walking in harmony again together.

35
00:03:13,060 --> 00:03:14,600
and what a blessing that was.

36
00:03:15,340 --> 00:03:17,700
Next Sunday, Elaine and I will be in Honolulu.

37
00:03:18,750 --> 00:03:20,010
Aww, you know.

38
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:23,000
Somebody's got to do it, folks.

39
00:03:24,560 --> 00:03:27,920
But First Baptist Honolulu went through a very difficult time

40
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:29,000
a year and a half ago,

41
00:03:29,540 --> 00:03:32,140
and we were very concerned about that church,

42
00:03:32,260 --> 00:03:33,880
but they've called a new pastor.

43
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:36,020
The church is growing again

44
00:03:36,020 --> 00:03:38,580
and is coming back together in many ways,

45
00:03:38,580 --> 00:03:40,640
and I'll be there for that pastor's installation.

46
00:03:41,140 --> 00:03:43,780
They've had a number of baptisms since he came,

47
00:03:43,780 --> 00:03:47,580
and it's going to be good to see what God is doing there.

48
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:51,060
And so that's a little bit about what's going on within our lives

49
00:03:51,060 --> 00:03:54,680
as Elaine and I travel and as we're absent from you so much of the time.

50
00:03:55,200 --> 00:03:59,140
But we're grateful for your prayer support for the churches across this region

51
00:03:59,140 --> 00:04:03,540
as we seek to strengthen congregations within their ministries.

52
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:06,520
Now, it's the Sunday before New Year's.

53
00:04:07,140 --> 00:04:09,080
And so I thought I'd bring you something special.

54
00:04:09,240 --> 00:04:10,400
This is not part of the sermon.

55
00:04:11,020 --> 00:04:13,480
I'll even take my watch off so I can see to it

56
00:04:13,480 --> 00:04:21,020
that I timed it correctly. There's a website, and I don't remember the exact letters of this

57
00:04:21,020 --> 00:04:26,200
website, but they give away the Idiot of the Year Award. And they haven't picked out the Idiot of

58
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:31,120
the Year for 2003 yet, but I went back and I checked 2002. And I thought, well, I've just got

59
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:36,120
to share this story so that you can be aware, you know, someone's going to get the prize for this

60
00:04:36,120 --> 00:04:41,520
year, but this one for last year really doesn't. It's a true story. It comes out of San Francisco.

61
00:04:41,520 --> 00:04:46,060
a man wanting to rob a downtown Bank of America

62
00:04:46,060 --> 00:04:49,320
walked into the branch bank and he wrote

63
00:04:49,320 --> 00:04:52,040
this is a stick-up

64
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:54,440
is spelled I-Z

65
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:57,840
stick-up spelled S-T-I-K-K-U-P

66
00:04:57,840 --> 00:05:02,580
put all your money spelled M-U-N-Y in this bag

67
00:05:02,580 --> 00:05:05,540
while he was standing in line

68
00:05:05,540 --> 00:05:07,100
waiting to give the note to the teller

69
00:05:07,100 --> 00:05:09,580
he began to worry that someone had seen him

70
00:05:09,580 --> 00:05:10,580
write the note

71
00:05:10,580 --> 00:05:14,100
and might call the police before he reached the teller's window.

72
00:05:14,840 --> 00:05:19,400
So he left the Bank of America, and he crossed the street to the Wells Fargo Bank.

73
00:05:20,600 --> 00:05:23,100
The lines were shorter there, and after a few minutes,

74
00:05:23,180 --> 00:05:25,840
he handed his note to the Wells Fargo teller.

75
00:05:26,660 --> 00:05:30,570
She read it, and surmising from his spelling errors

76
00:05:30,570 --> 00:05:32,890
that he wasn't the brightest light in the harbor,

77
00:05:33,730 --> 00:05:36,930
told him that she could not accept his stick-up note

78
00:05:36,930 --> 00:05:39,950
because it was written on a Bank of America deposit slip.

79
00:05:39,950 --> 00:05:47,320
and that he would either have to fill out a Wells Fargo deposit slip

80
00:05:47,320 --> 00:05:49,440
or go back to the Bank of America.

81
00:05:52,400 --> 00:05:58,340
Looking somewhat defeated, the man said, okay, and he left.

82
00:05:59,280 --> 00:06:03,200
He was arrested a few minutes later, standing in the line of the Bank of America.

83
00:06:05,330 --> 00:06:07,670
You can see why he got the award last year.

84
00:06:09,090 --> 00:06:11,270
Well, I'm looking forward to see who gets it this year.

85
00:06:13,660 --> 00:06:17,740
In your bulletin, you should find a sermon note sheet that looks kind of like this

86
00:06:17,740 --> 00:06:22,180
that will help you follow as we study this morning and I'd invite you to turn with me to

87
00:06:22,180 --> 00:06:27,720
the book of Philippians the third chapter where we find our text this morning Philippians chapter

88
00:06:27,720 --> 00:06:48,570
3 verses 4 through 11 Philippians 3 4 through 11 Paul writes there though I myself have reasons

89
00:06:48,570 --> 00:06:55,690
for such confidence if anyone else thinks he has reasons to put confidence in the flesh

90
00:06:55,690 --> 00:06:57,540
I have more.

91
00:06:59,130 --> 00:07:01,930
Circumcised on the eighth day of the people of Israel,

92
00:07:02,550 --> 00:07:03,630
the tribe of Benjamin,

93
00:07:04,640 --> 00:07:06,280
a Hebrew of the Hebrews.

94
00:07:07,380 --> 00:07:10,040
In regard to the law, a Pharisee.

95
00:07:11,040 --> 00:07:14,160
As for zeal, persecuting the church.

96
00:07:15,420 --> 00:07:19,080
As for legalistic righteousness, faultless.

97
00:07:20,940 --> 00:07:23,880
But whatever I thought was to my profit,

98
00:07:23,880 --> 00:07:28,360
I now consider loss for the sake of Christ.

99
00:07:28,860 --> 00:07:35,640
What is more, I consider everything a loss compared to the surpassing greatness of knowing

100
00:07:35,640 --> 00:07:41,310
Christ Jesus, my Lord, for whose sake I've suffered the loss of all things.

101
00:07:41,870 --> 00:07:49,530
I consider them rubbish that I may gain Christ and be found in him not having a righteousness

102
00:07:49,530 --> 00:07:56,140
of my own that comes from the law, but that which is through faith in Christ, a righteousness

103
00:07:56,140 --> 00:07:59,600
that comes from God and is by faith.

104
00:08:01,070 --> 00:08:07,790
I want to know Christ and the power of his resurrection and the fellowship of the sharing

105
00:08:07,790 --> 00:08:16,610
in his sufferings, becoming like him in his death, and so somehow to attain to the resurrection

106
00:08:16,610 --> 00:08:27,880
from the dead. This morning, I want you to focus with me on how Paul knew he could be certain about

107
00:08:27,880 --> 00:08:36,730
his salvation and suggest to you that there's only one way that you can be sure. Some of you

108
00:08:36,730 --> 00:08:42,490
might be here this morning looking for a relationship with God and you wonder how it

109
00:08:42,490 --> 00:08:48,100
is you can build that relationship. This morning what I'm going to be speaking of is the heart of

110
00:08:48,100 --> 00:08:54,010
the Christian message and I'm going to try to make it as clear to you as I can what is absolutely

111
00:08:54,010 --> 00:09:02,250
unique about Christian faith. I'll show you how you can put your faith in Christ. Most of us here

112
00:09:02,250 --> 00:09:09,200
have known the Lord a long time and I've seen particularly in the last six years as I've been

113
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:15,240
in church after church after church that one of the great reasons why churches sometimes grow

114
00:09:15,240 --> 00:09:22,120
cold and indifferent and passive in their ministries is that people lose contact with

115
00:09:22,120 --> 00:09:28,120
the central reality of the Christian faith, what God has done for them in Christ. If we keep hold

116
00:09:28,120 --> 00:09:34,840
of that firmly, there is no way that you can become cold or indifferent or passive about what

117
00:09:34,840 --> 00:09:41,250
God has done for you. A number of years ago Elaine and I were in a mall in Lockport, New York where I

118
00:09:41,250 --> 00:09:46,370
used to be pastor and we were going by this little dress shop called the Deb Shop. One of our members

119
00:09:46,370 --> 00:09:53,440
was the manager there and in the window of the shop it said going out of business sale. Well I

120
00:09:53,440 --> 00:10:00,920
was alarmed because I knew the manager Tracy Lanahan so well and what puzzled me though was

121
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:07,020
it said, second annual going out of business sale. And so I went in and I said to Tracy,

122
00:10:07,180 --> 00:10:13,690
Tracy, how can anybody have a second annual going out of business sale? She said, we got you. You

123
00:10:13,690 --> 00:10:20,390
didn't read it carefully. I looked again, and what it said was, second annual going out for

124
00:10:20,390 --> 00:10:27,140
business sale. She said, that sign is a real attention getter, and I have to admit, it worked

125
00:10:27,140 --> 00:10:36,190
on me. My dad managed a department store when I was growing up, and my first jobs were all working

126
00:10:36,190 --> 00:10:41,190
for my dad. As a 12-year-old, he hired me in the toy department at Christmas time to run the electric

127
00:10:41,190 --> 00:10:46,590
train display. I mean, pay a kid 50 cents an hour to run the trains, and that's a happy kid.

128
00:10:47,550 --> 00:10:53,230
Later in high school, I worked as a stock boy and then began to work in sales, and when I was in

129
00:10:53,230 --> 00:10:57,810
college, I was managing some of his departments, and I absolutely loved working with dad, and

130
00:10:57,810 --> 00:11:02,890
in the store. There were a lot of things he taught me during those years. One of the things he taught

131
00:11:02,890 --> 00:11:08,290
was that in his mind there were only two things that were essential to really running a successful

132
00:11:08,290 --> 00:11:15,620
retail business. And the first one is you've got to get people's attention. And to get their

133
00:11:15,620 --> 00:11:22,800
attention you've got to advertise, advertise, advertise. Young people who deliver newspapers

134
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:28,320
gain muscles Christmas time because of all the bulk of advertisement that's gone on within our

135
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:34,960
newspapers. And I can remember Dad going over the ads before they'd go in the paper, and then after

136
00:11:34,960 --> 00:11:39,520
they'd go in the paper. Sometimes there'd be mistakes, and if the mistakes were made by the

137
00:11:39,520 --> 00:11:46,210
newspaper, then we said the newspaper was responsible. If the mistakes were ours, then we

138
00:11:46,210 --> 00:11:51,230
took responsibility for it. But Dad always checked those things. There are some people who should

139
00:11:51,230 --> 00:11:58,020
check their ads. Ran across some advertisements that were rather interesting. This one was a sign

140
00:11:58,020 --> 00:12:00,640
that was in a shop at a mall at Christmastime.

141
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:04,460
It said, handmade gifts for the hard-to-find person.

142
00:12:07,570 --> 00:12:10,830
This one was a want ad, which I thought was really neat.

143
00:12:11,740 --> 00:12:12,680
Dog for sale.

144
00:12:13,630 --> 00:12:16,110
Eats anything and is fond of children.

145
00:12:18,120 --> 00:12:19,920
That tender meat is just so good.

146
00:12:21,560 --> 00:12:24,840
Then there was a sign that was actually over a counter at a store.

147
00:12:24,840 --> 00:12:28,220
It said, special price, stock up and save.

148
00:12:28,580 --> 00:12:29,480
Limit one.

149
00:12:32,210 --> 00:12:35,770
Well, Dad tried to check the ads to make sure we didn't make mistakes like that.

150
00:12:36,030 --> 00:12:42,250
The second thing Dad said is to succeed in business, you needed to sell what people want.

151
00:12:42,250 --> 00:12:44,610
And to do that, you needed to know your customers.

152
00:12:45,590 --> 00:12:47,970
And one thing my dad really knew was his customers.

153
00:12:48,630 --> 00:12:52,890
I can remember him opening up boxes that were sent to us by a manufacturer,

154
00:12:53,390 --> 00:12:58,450
and he would look at it, he would close it up at times, and he'd put it right back on the truck.

155
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:03,180
And then he'd tell me that was not the line that I asked for.

156
00:13:03,280 --> 00:13:04,860
That was a lower quality line.

157
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:06,340
They might be able to fool some people.

158
00:13:06,420 --> 00:13:07,140
They can't fool me.

159
00:13:07,200 --> 00:13:08,680
I'm not going to sell that to my customers.

160
00:13:08,820 --> 00:13:09,740
And back it would go.

161
00:13:10,380 --> 00:13:12,560
And his customers absolutely loved him for it.

162
00:13:12,660 --> 00:13:16,300
There was a loyalty that was there that he built over the years.

163
00:13:17,530 --> 00:13:19,610
Some customers were hard to please, though.

164
00:13:20,470 --> 00:13:22,510
You know, there are always customers that you can't please.

165
00:13:22,510 --> 00:13:28,310
One woman came in, and I'd swear she tried on every pair of women's shoes in the shoe department this particular day.

166
00:13:28,310 --> 00:13:32,050
and didn't see anything she liked, and she finally said to the salesperson,

167
00:13:32,250 --> 00:13:33,610
don't you have anything else?

168
00:13:33,650 --> 00:13:35,370
And the woman said, only the shoes I'm wearing.

169
00:13:35,470 --> 00:13:37,150
She said, well, I like them. Are they for sale?

170
00:13:42,140 --> 00:13:47,580
Some people think of religion as a business proposition.

171
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:53,020
And you can tell from my talking about my dad that I love the world of business.

172
00:13:53,780 --> 00:13:57,100
But the world of religion is not the same as a business proposition.

173
00:13:57,440 --> 00:14:01,080
People think that if we build up a stock of good deeds,

174
00:14:01,080 --> 00:14:06,180
that then we try to sell them to God in exchange for eternal life.

175
00:14:06,320 --> 00:14:08,840
So it's kind of a business transaction that we do.

176
00:14:09,400 --> 00:14:13,060
Let's see, I made 52 trips to church this year,

177
00:14:13,700 --> 00:14:16,160
and some of those services went more than an hour,

178
00:14:16,300 --> 00:14:17,300
so that's a little bit more.

179
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:20,040
And I always put something in the offering,

180
00:14:20,120 --> 00:14:22,500
so that's $52 over the course of a year.

181
00:14:23,820 --> 00:14:26,940
There are some people who let that offering plate go by, but I won't.

182
00:14:26,940 --> 00:14:29,100
Of course, I had to make change a few times.

183
00:14:30,260 --> 00:14:30,920
Let's see.

184
00:14:31,240 --> 00:14:33,460
I attended six meetings of the church board.

185
00:14:33,580 --> 00:14:35,080
That really ought to count for something.

186
00:14:35,720 --> 00:14:41,180
And I donated my worn-out shoes and grandma's pink doilies to the rummage sale.

187
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:42,300
That counts for something.

188
00:14:42,700 --> 00:14:44,700
And I voted Republican in the fall election.

189
00:14:44,820 --> 00:14:45,900
That should count for something.

190
00:14:46,520 --> 00:14:48,520
Okay, Lord, that's a pretty good selection.

191
00:14:48,700 --> 00:14:50,460
You ought to find something you like there, Lord.

192
00:14:54,370 --> 00:15:00,960
Every other religion in the world functions basically like a business proposition,

193
00:15:00,960 --> 00:15:03,160
except for Christianity.

194
00:15:04,150 --> 00:15:05,750
In every other religion in the world,

195
00:15:05,870 --> 00:15:07,570
we say, here God, here's my good works,

196
00:15:07,650 --> 00:15:09,390
I hope there's something that you're going to buy there

197
00:15:09,390 --> 00:15:12,450
and in exchange, I want the gift of eternal life.

198
00:15:14,050 --> 00:15:14,990
There's just one problem.

199
00:15:16,570 --> 00:15:19,630
What if God is not impressed with my merchandise

200
00:15:19,630 --> 00:15:22,100
and he just won't buy it?

201
00:15:23,710 --> 00:15:27,130
In business, your stock is only an asset

202
00:15:27,130 --> 00:15:27,970
if you can sell it.

203
00:15:29,150 --> 00:15:32,470
If you can't sell it and it hangs around long enough,

204
00:15:32,570 --> 00:15:33,370
it's a liability.

205
00:15:33,790 --> 00:15:35,210
That's just plain how it works.

206
00:15:35,210 --> 00:15:39,130
And too much unsold inventory leads to bankruptcy.

207
00:15:41,280 --> 00:15:45,900
So what happens if you and I build up this great stock of good deeds

208
00:15:45,900 --> 00:15:50,190
that we're sure that God will buy, and then he doesn't buy it?

209
00:15:51,790 --> 00:15:54,210
The Bible says that that is our problem.

210
00:15:55,630 --> 00:15:57,470
Isaiah 64 verse 6 says,

211
00:15:58,130 --> 00:16:02,170
All our righteous acts are like filthy rags in God's sight.

212
00:16:02,810 --> 00:16:05,510
And who wants to buy a pile of filthy rags?

213
00:16:06,760 --> 00:16:10,900
Galatians 2.16 says, by observing the works of the law, no one can be justified.

214
00:16:13,800 --> 00:16:16,660
In the passage that we read in Philippians, the third chapter,

215
00:16:17,480 --> 00:16:20,180
the Apostle Paul explains that there was a time in his life

216
00:16:20,180 --> 00:16:24,060
when he thought of religion as a kind of business proposition.

217
00:16:25,450 --> 00:16:31,670
Paul believed that he had accumulated an impressive array of religious stock to offer God.

218
00:16:32,810 --> 00:16:34,790
Impeccable credentials, good deeds,

219
00:16:34,970 --> 00:16:37,690
and he was certain that God was going to buy the whole store

220
00:16:37,690 --> 00:16:43,770
and give him eternal life that's what he's saying in verses four to six look at how he says it

221
00:16:43,770 --> 00:16:50,670
i myself have reason for such confidence if anyone thinks he has reason to put confidence in the

222
00:16:50,670 --> 00:16:58,770
flesh i have more circumcised the eighth day of the people of israel the tribe of benjamin

223
00:16:58,770 --> 00:17:04,510
